dataIdInfo.idAbs: Annual Five-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for 2000 to 2025 for the national, and first- and second-order administrative division levels of Ethiopia were prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau for joining (linking) to shapefiles as attribute data. The estimates are consistent with the midyear national projections from the U.S. Census Bureau International Data Base (IDB).
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for Ethiopia for 2000-2025 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. Presidentâ€™s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
dataIdInfo.idCredit:
CENSUS DATA Age-Sex data: 2007 Population and Housing Census Report, Table 2.8: Population by Urban-Rural Residence, Sex, and Five Year Age Groups to 95+. Ethiopia Central Statistics Agency. Available online at http://www.csa.gov.et/census-report/complete-report/census-2007 (region-level PDFs must be downloaded individually, accessed June 03, 2020); 1994 Population and Housing Census Report, Table 2.1: Total Population Size of Zones and Weredas by Sex, Urban and Rural. Ethiopia Central Statistics Agency. Available online at http://www.csa.gov.et/census-report/complete-report/census-1994 (region-level PDFs must be downloaded individually, accessed June 03, 2020). Population data for the special enumeration areas of Region 17 were acquired from the Summary and Statistical Report of the 2007 Population and Housing Census, Table 3: Population Size of Regions, Zones and Weredas by Place of Residence and Sex. Federal Democratic Republic of Ethiopia Population Census Commission. Available online at http://ecastats.uneca.org/aicmd/Portals/0/Cen2007_firstdraft.pdf (accessed June 03, 2020). The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of non-U.S. census and survey data.
GEOSPATIAL BOUNDARIES International boundaries coincide with the Large Scale International Boundaries (LSIB) dataset from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Available online at http://geonode.state.gov (accessed June 03, 2020). Geospatial data for the second-order administrative divisions of Ethiopia were downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange at http://data.humdata.org/dataset/ethiopia-administrative-boundary-level-3, "Ethiopia - Administrative Boundary Level 3" (accessed July 11, 2016, no longer available online). The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of boundary placements.
NATIONAL ESTIMATES AND PROJECTIONS U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division. International Data Base, December 2019 release, available online at http://www.census.gov/data-tools/demo/idb/informationGateway.php, accessed June 03, 2020.
NATIONAL AND SUBNATIONAL AREA NAMES AND CODES (1) U.S. National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency. NGA GEOnet Names Server (GNS), available at http://geonames.nga.mil/gns/html/ (accessed June 04, 2020). Contains geographic area names from the U.S. Board on Geographic Names and the U.S. Government Federal Information Processing System (FIPS) codes. (2) U.S. Government Geopolitical Entities, Names, and Codes (GENC) Standard. NSG Standards Registry, available at http://nsgreg.nga.mil/genc/discovery (accessed June 04, 2020).

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
SUBNATIONAL DIVISIONS Ethiopia's second-order administrative divisions: 78 zones and special enumeration areas as of the 2007 census.
SHAPEFILES The original shapefile downloaded from the Humanitarian Data Exchange had 690 polygons and matched the 2007 census weredas, towns, and sub-cities (third-order administrative divisions), after a change to the subnational boundaries by USCB staff: (1) 67 polygons were added to the original shapefile, mostly representing town boundaries. The township boundaries were traced by USCB staff from ArcGIS Basemap imagery. This change resulted in a shapefile with 757 polygons, one for each of Ethiopia's third-order administrative divisions. The U.S. Census Bureau aligned the shapefile's national boundary to the Large Scale International Boundary Line (LSIB) polygon file from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Finally, the LSIB-aligned shapefile was dissolved into 78 polygons, one for each of Ethiopia's second-order administrative divisions (zones and special enumeration areas) as reported by the Ethiopia Central Statistics Agency in the 2007 census.
CENSUS DATA INTERPOLATION The 1994 census totals had the following differences in geography that have been modified to their 2007 locations in the estimates presented here, requiring interpolation and adjustment of 1994 population data by USCB staff: (1) At the time of its 1994 population census, Ethiopia's first-order administrative divisions consisted of 8 regions, 2 chartered cities, and the capital district, all comprised of 66 zones and 518 weredas. (2) Of Ethiopia's 757 third-order administrative divisions present at the time of the 2007 census, the boundaries of 297 remained unchanged since the 1994 census, 381 were formed from part of a single wereda from 1994, and 79 were formed from parts of multiple weredas from 1994, as noted in the USCBCMNT field. Many of the third-order administrative areas from 1994 no longer existed by 2007. (3) The Robinson Projection was used by USCB staff to calculate the areas, in square kilometers, of weredas that were formed from parts of multiple other weredas. For new weredas, towns, and sub-cities that were fully formed from part of a single area, where boundaries and population data were not available for the next administrative level down, the total population of the original area in 1994 was divided proportionally according to the populations of the new areas in 2007. For new weredas, towns, and sub-cities that were formed from parts of multiple original areas, where boundaries and population data were not available for the next administrative level down, the total population of the new area in 2007 was divided proportionally according to the land areas of the multiple original pieces in square kilometers.
ADDITIONAL NOTES (1) Sub-cities of Ä€dÄ«s Ä€beba listed in the 2007 census were formed from weredas listed in the 1994 census, and are being treated as third-level administrative divisions for the purposes of this product. (2) DirÄ“ Dawa and DirÄ“ Dawa Town, along with the special enumeration areas of Region 17 are second-level administrative divisions being treated as third-level administrative divisions for the purposes of this product.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS The 2000-2025 population estimates for Ethiopia's administrative divisions are provided in the following two tables: (1) The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Ethiopia_5yr_age_sex_2000-2025_uscb_aug2020.txt," which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field "GEOMATCH." (2) The Excel table "Ethiopia_5yr_age_sex_2000-2025_508_uscb_aug2020.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government's Federal Rehabilitation Act.
Details on processing of the census data and calculation of 2000-2025 estimates are provided in the "Census Metadata" tab of the Excel file and "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas" document. For the subnational areas, the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) "approved" names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in the "Credits") were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country's national statistical office, when available, are entered in the "NSO_CODE" field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternative area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the "USCBCMNT" field. A partial list of the fields in the Excel and Unicode text files, including all fields identifying geographic names and codes, is provided in the Excel file's "Data Dictionary" tab. More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." It includes a data dictionary that is similar to that in the Excel table.
METHODOLOGY For more information, see the following methodology documents in the Spatial Data Repository: (1) "U.S. Census Bureau Methodology for SDR Subnational Population Estimates." (2) "U.S. Census Bureau Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas." (3) "Instructions for Joining Subnational Population Data to Shapefiles."
ACCESS The U.S. Census Bureauâ€™s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the Spatial Data Repository at http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/, which also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program. A zipped file containing shapefiles with metadata, an Excel workbook with subnational population estimates, and a Unicode tab-delimited text file is available for each country. PEPFAR products are also available on the Census Bureau website at http://www.census.gov/geographies/mapping-files/time-series/demo/international-programs/subnationalpopulation.html for download.
